Stars like Mary Pickford, Charlie Chaplin, and Douglas Fairbanks became vitally important and companies began writing high-profile contracts to secure them. With the outbreak of World War I, the political, economic, and industrial groundwork was laid for American cinema's global dominance. By the end of the decade, filmmaking had become a true industry, complete with vertical integration, efficient specialization and standardization of practices, and self-regulatory agencies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxPlots, themes, etc. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aAbel, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowser, Eileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeBauche, Leslie Midkiffe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrieveson, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeil, Charlie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeil, Charlie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKing, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLatham, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimmon, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinger, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinger, Ben, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStamp, Shelley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354654440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813546